  "doc_id": "46573",
  "text": "Although lung cancer is a major cause of death from cancer in Japan, anaplastic lymphoma kinase (ALK) inhibitors have produced remarkable clinical responses compared with those produced by standard cytotoxic chemotherapy in nonsmall cell lung cancer (NSCLC) harboring an ALK rearrangement [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma (LCNEC) is a relatively rare lung tumor. Pulmonary LCNEC is biologically aggressive, similarly to small-cell lung cancer (SCLC). The survival curves of pulmonary LCNEC and SCLC overlap at every stage, and the survival is lower in them than in other NSCLCs (3). To our knowledge, only two cases of a pulmonary LCNEC harboring an ALK rearrangement have been reported (4, 5).",
